<div class="hero">
  <h1>UK migration statistics are often discussed as if they are one number. They are not.</h1>
  <p class="lede">Migration, immigration, net migration and asylum are different things,
  counted in different ways, over different periods. This site shows what each figure
  actually measures, and what it does not.</p>
</div>

{#- The distinctions come before the figures, deliberately. See foundation section 8.1. -#}
<ul class="panels">
  <li class="panel">
    <h2>Migration is not the same as asylum</h2>
    <p>Asylum is one route among several. Study and work were both larger in the most
    recent year. <a href="/common-claims/most-immigration-is-asylum/">See the figures</a>.</p>
  </li>
  <li class="panel">
    <h2>Net migration is not arrivals</h2>
    <p>It is arrivals minus departures, a balance between two much larger numbers.
    <a href="/common-claims/net-migration-is-arrivals/">See why that matters</a>.</p>
  </li>
  <li class="panel">
    <h2>A visa granted is not a person arriving</h2>
    {#- Named for what it goes to, not for the page it lives on. As "What the words mean"
        it was the second link on this page with that exact text, and the other one, in the
        nav, goes to the top of the glossary rather than to this term. It also read
        differently from the two panels beside it, which name what you will find. -#}
    <p>Permission is not a journey. Some visas are never used, and some are extensions for
    people already here. <a href="/what-the-words-mean/#visa-grant">What a visa grant counts</a>.</p>
  </li>
</ul>

<h2>The headline figures</h2>

<p>Each figure below states what it counts and over what period, because without those two
things a number on this subject is not information. Each also shows its source, when that
source was published, and
<a href="/sources-and-method/#confidence">this site's own confidence grade</a> for it. The
grade is our judgement about how far the figure can be relied on, not the publisher's.</p>

<ul class="cards">
  {%- for card in dashboard.cards %}
  {%- set m = card.ref | metric %}
  <li class="card">
    <h3>{{ card.shortLabel }}</h3>
    {%- set symbolised = m.unit == "%" or m.unit == "£ billion" %}
    <span class="value">{% if m.unit == "£ billion" %}£{% endif %}{{ m.value | number }}{% if m.unit == "%" %}%{% endif %}{% if m.unit == "£ billion" %} billion{% endif %}</span>
    <span class="period">{% if not symbolised %}{{ m.unit }} · {% endif %}{{ m.period_label }}</span>
    <p class="means">{{ card.whatThisMeans }}</p>
    <p class="source"><a href="{{ m.source_url }}">{{ m.source_name }}</a><br>
    {#- Foundation 2.1 promises that where a publication date is not recorded the figure says
        so rather than guessing. There was no branch here, and longDate returns an empty
        string for a null, so the card would have rendered "Published" followed by nothing,
        which reads as a date that failed to load rather than one that was never published. -#}
    {% if m.published_date %}Published {{ m.published_date | longDate }}{% else %}Publication date not recorded{% endif %}<br>
    {#- The date we last checked the figure against its source, which is a different thing
        from when the source published it. A reader judging whether this site is up to date
        needs the second, and it was only ever in the data files. Foundation 17. -#}
    Checked {{ m.retrieved_date | longDate }}<br>
    <span class="grade">{{ m.confidence_level }}</span></p>
  </li>
  {%- endfor %}
</ul>

<h2>Before you compare these figures</h2>

<p>They do not all cover the same period, and they do not all count the same kind of thing.
Some count people, one counts grants, one is a share of the population and one is money
spent. Set out together, the periods are:</p>

{#- Generated from the cards themselves. The previous version of this paragraph described a
    card set that did not exist: it named routes with no card and miscounted the ones there
    were. A paragraph whose whole job is period discipline cannot be maintained by hand. -#}
<ul class="periods">
  {%- for card in dashboard.cards %}
  {%- set m = card.ref | metric %}
  <li><strong>{{ card.shortLabel }}</strong>: {{ m.period_label }}</li>
  {%- endfor %}
</ul>

<p>Comparing a figure from one of those windows with a figure from another, and calling the
difference a change, is not valid.</p>

